Environment Variables
Environment variables are special variables that affect the way processes run on your system. They are often used to store system-wide values like the location of executables or the default editor.
v


[root@localhost scripting]# cat environmental_var.sh
echo "this is your $PATH"

[root@localhost scripting]# bash environmental_var.sh
this is your /root/.local/bin:/root/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin
[root@localhost scripting]#


---Local variables are only available within the block of code in which they are defined, such as within a function. Global variables are accessible from anywhere in the script.


[root@localhost scripting]# cat funct.sh
#!/bin/bash

my_function () {
        local_var="am local person"
        echo "$local_var"
}
my_function
[root@localhost scripting]# bash funct.sh
am local person
[root@localhost scripting]#
